    # [Scene: Harbor Pier | Early Evening]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, restless strings; distant gulls]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Drum of footsteps on planks, muffled chants swelling]
    "You stand where the pier narrows, the crowd pressing behind you like a slow-moving tide. Rain threads the air—fine, persistent—flattening hair and banner fabric, making the painted letters run at the edges. The compass in your pocket presses against your hip as if sensing the pull of what you've chosen."

    "Your voice is hoarse already from calling people into place, but you keep speaking. Instructions are small, practical things" "Anchor the banner here,' 'Keep the generator clear,' 'Two people on the scaffold with the reef modules."
    show luca_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_moreno "You're louder than I expected, Isla. That's a good thing.' (He readjusts a strap.) 'You ready to get your hands covered in reef goo?"
    "You laugh—it's thin, but real—and step up onto the scaffolding. The wood gives a complaint under your boots. Up close, the demonstration reef modules look clumsy and beautiful: bundles of reclaimed oyster shells, woven with mesh"
    "and seeded with native eelgrass plugs. People pass them hand-to-hand like offerings. Your fingers find the cold center of a module and grip."
    "You work with Luca. The tasks are physical; the intimacy of labor is more urgent than words. Salt dries in the crook of your arms as you fasten another loop, your palms and forearms registering the"
    "texture of rope, the sting of sea spray. He forgets to let go of something; his hand bumps yours. Neither of you say anything, but the small shrug between you is a private sentence."

    menu:
        "Climb higher to secure the top module":
            "You hoist yourself up, breath sharp in your chest, and secure the top brace. From your vantage the town fans out like a map, and for a second the project feels possible."
        "Stay low and coordinate people on the pier":
            "You stay with the crowd, voice carving space through the noise—directing, calming. You see faces rearrange; decisions you didn't make suddenly happen because you were there to steer them."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues as written below."

    luca_moreno "Good call—both of them,' he says after a beat. 'Your timing's precise. Don't vanish on me after this; I need someone to tell me I didn't dream it."
    show isla_morgan at right:
        zoom 0.7

    isla_morgan "I won't disappear.' (Your voice is steadier than your pulse.) 'But I won't pretend this won't hurt people either."
    "He looks at you, and the grin softens into something like worry. He has that tendency—wants to fix the world with braces and bolts and a smile. You appreciate it and fear it. The reef goes"
    "into the surf; the first modules sink with a collective, slurping release, and a cheer ripples through the crowd."

    "Around you, chants build and unwind—practical, urgent lines" "Our town, our tide!' 'Save the flats, not corporate walls!"
    "Then a voice cuts through, controlled and exact: Aria Chen's public address—amplified and elegant. Her arrival is announced by the metallic click of her council badge, by the rustle of a briefcase, by a small pocket of polished authority that never quite blends into the damp weather around her."
    show aria_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_chen "This demonstration is disruptive and ill-timed,' she says, voice measured so every syllable lands like a coin on wood. 'We have a process. We have timelines. This—' (She gestures at the reef modules and the people) '—is not the way to build consensus."
    "You step forward before you decide to. You sense the crowd lean into the space between you. People are watching both of you the way a tide watches two rocks."

    isla_morgan "Consensus isn't built when decisions are already sold,' you say. (You keep your tone even; irritation is a dangerous thing on a wet pier.) 'We're showing an alternative that won't hollow out the flats to pay for short-term jobs."
    "Aria Chen: (A half-smile that doesn't reach her eyes.) 'Isla, you always make arguments into absolutes. There are jobs on the line. There are families—'"

    isla_morgan "There are also long-term losses, and we're not willing to hand the town's future to promises that wash away."

    aria_chen "And you're willing to risk immediate livelihoods for theoretical long-term gains?"
    "The interruption is immediate. A woman from the fish market—hands stained with old bait—shoves into the conversation, voice raw."

    "Market Woman" "You want us to wait for some future that may never pay our bills? Some of us can't afford that patience, Miss Chen."
    "Aria Chen: (Faltering, then finding a practiced cadence.) 'I'm proposing a plan that brings investment. Jobs provide stability—'"

    luca_moreno "Stability bought at the cost of our shoreline isn't stability at all,' he snaps, louder than you expect. (He looks at you, and there is apology in the set of his jaw, like a note passed across a crowded room.) 'We can create jobs with the reef—maintenance, monitoring—real, local work."
    "The exchange spirals—voices overlap, fingers point, and the rain grows heavier, as if the sky is trying to wash the argument clean. The tension is the kind that makes your teeth hurt. You're trying to hold the center of a conversation that refuses to be contained."
    "Then—sudden, physical—the crowd stumbles into panic. An elder fisherman collapses near the rail: his knees give out and his head drops forward. He is not a name you can fetch from memory; he's one of the"
    "faces that have always been in the background of town life, a presence like a weathered wall. Panic is a short, sharp smell—metallic and wet."
    "Jonah Merrick is at his side immediately. Old hands find the man's shoulders and lift, voice low and full of old calm."
    hide luca_moreno
    show jonah_merrick at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_merrick "Easy, now—breathe, boy. Breathe.' (He steadies the fisherman like he'd steady a boat in a chop.) 'Someone fetch a blanket. Give him space."
    "You are halfway across the pier before your mind can name why your chest has tightened so sharply. Guilt blooms—a small, hot thing—because you feel, with awkward clarity, that your decision to force the issue has pressed heat onto the town's already-tender skin."
    "You kneel as Jonah instructs, and the crowd folds around you like a tide pulling back. The chants stutter. For the first time in hours, your hands are not making policy or reef modules but pressing into the ocean of someone else's crisis."
    "Ravi: (kneeling opposite you, breath rapid) 'He said his chest—no, he's breathing—keep him warm.' (His hands are steady even though his voice shakes.)"

    isla_morgan "Someone call the clinic. Now,"
    "Jonah Merrick: (folding his jacket under the man's head) 'This is why things get hard. People get afraid, and fear orders them to pick the nearest lifeline.' (He looks at you, not unkind, but heavy with history.) 'You meant to help, Isla. Meaning doesn't stop the hurt that follows.'"

    isla_morgan "I know.' (Your reply is a taut string.) 'I know I can't make everyone choose what I think is right."

    jonah_merrick "But remember—people judge by what stays."
    "The confrontation with Aria resumes in fits and starts—arguments folded into care for the man who collapsed, into whispered consultations and the flash of someone dialing a phone. Aria's expression shifts; the polished veneer fractures into visible stress. She changes tactics, suddenly quickening her words."

    aria_chen "Because of tonight's disruption, the council will accelerate the timetable. We cannot have more demonstrations before the vote."
    "Luca Moreno: (bitter laugh) 'Accelerate into what? A secrecy vote? A rushed contract with developers?' (He looks at you like the world is a set of levers he wants to pry.)"

    aria_chen "We are balancing needs.' (Her tone says you are naive and he is reckless.) 'I want to work with people who want solutions."

    isla_morgan "Solutions—real ones—need community involvement, not backroom deals."
    "The crowd splinters into accusations. Some people shout support—others shout that you've jeopardized wages. The market woman returns, face hard."

    "Market Woman" "You two are tearing the town apart. People who depend on the docks are frightened—you're making them more so."
    "You: (Your internal monologue sharp as flint.) You had hoped passion could be bridged with data, and that urgency would translate into care. Instead the choice has become binary in people's mouths: jobs or preservation. The"
    "truth is messier, and the guilt of having pushed the needle sharpens into something like responsibility."

    menu:
        "Step forward and invite Aria to inspect the reef modules up close":
            "You hold out your hand and gesture. For a beat the world narrows to two people and the wet wood between them. Aria hesitates, then walks the planks. Her jaw tightens as she studies the modules; the crowd murmurs. You feel the fragile possibility of contact, but you also feel the eyes of those who accuse you of wasting time."
        "Hold your ground and keep rallying the crowd":
            "You turn back to the megaphone. Your voice cuts through the drizzle again and the chant resumes. People find energy in the rhythm, and fear turns back into action—but somewhere near the edges, resentment hardens like salt on rope."

